Title: Radial Basis Functions
Date: 2015-08-12

<p>In this document Iâ€™ll explain some nice characteristics of radial basis functions.</p>
<div id="introduction" class="section level3">
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>A radial basis function is a real-valued function whose value depends only on the distance from the origin. For example;</p>

$$ \phi_i(x) = exp\left(-\frac{1}{2\alpha}(x-m_i)^2\right)$$ 

<pre class="r"><code>x = seq(-2,5,0.01) 
y = exp(-1/0.5*(x)^2)
rbf_df &lt;- data.frame(x=x, y=y, m='0')
for(i in 1:4){
  rbf_df &lt;- rbind(rbf_df, data.frame(x=x, y=exp(-1/0.5*(x-i)^2), m=as.character(i)))
}
ggplot() + 
  geom_line(data=rbf_df, aes(x,y, colour=m)) + 
  ggtitle('different RBFs for different &quot;m&quot;')</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="use-case-in-pattern-learning" class="section level3">
<h3>Use case in pattern learning</h3>
<p>These functions have interesting uses in pattern learning, especially in situations where there is a repeating pattern. The ideal will be to take a continous area and to place evenly spaced radial basis functions.</p>
<p>To keep things simple, Iâ€™ll assume that <span class="math">\(\alpha = 1\)</span>, which reduces the expression to;</p>

$$ \phi_i(x) = exp\left(\frac{1}{2}(x-m_i)^2\right)$$ 

<p>Iâ€™ll now generate some data and use this function to generate features from it. Letâ€™s assume that I am generating data that is happening in a year over a period of 12 months.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- c(seq(0, 12, 0.01))
y &lt;- sin(x) + 2*cos(x/2) + rnorm(length(x), 0 , 0.2)
df &lt;- data.frame(x = x, y = y)

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data=df, aes(x, y), alpha=0.4) + 
  ggtitle('created data')</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>This data might be sales for a certain product that does better in colder periods of the year as opposed to warmer periods of the year.</p>
<p>Now I will generate features for this dataset. First, Iâ€™ll add dummy variables, one for each month and then Iâ€™ll add radial basis functions with means around the same month.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df$z = floor(x) %&gt;% as.factor

for(m in 1:12){
  df[[paste0('x', m)]] &lt;- exp(-1/2*(x-m)^2)
}</code></pre>
<p>I will now create two models;</p>
<ul>
<li>one will use dummy variables for each month (1-12) and instead those into a linear model</li>
<li>the other will use 12 radial basis functions, each simulating a month</li>
</ul>

The first model will try to find appropriate values $\beta_i$ for a regression with dummy variables only. If $m_i(x)$ is indicator function that tells us if we are in month $i$ then the regression task becomes finding proper $\beta_i$ values for; 

$$ \hat{y}(x) = \sum_i \hat{\beta_i} m_i(x) + \epsilon$$ 

The latter model will try to find appropriate values $\beta_i$ for the following regression;

$$ \hat{y}(x) = \sum_i \hat{\beta_i} \phi_i(x) + \epsilon$$ 

Note that both these models are using the same algorithm, whats different is that each model receives different features that get generated from the data. 

<pre class="r"><code>df$pred_floor &lt;- lm(y ~ ., data=df %&gt;% select(y, z)) %&gt;% predict(df)
df$pred_rad &lt;- lm(y ~ 0 + ., data=df %&gt;% select(-x, -z, -pred_floor)) %&gt;% predict(df)
ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data=df, aes(x, y), alpha = 0.4) + 
  geom_line(data=df, aes(x, pred_floor), color='red', size = 1) +
  geom_line(data=df, aes(x, pred_rad), color='steelblue', size = 1) + 
  ggtitle('dummy variables (red) vs. RBFs (blue)')</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>We can already see that the basis radial function can help us smoothe out any seasonality effects. Still, when we look at the model summary we get the impression that not all model inputs are significant.</p>

<p>There are other ways of determining if we should include a rbf in our model but this method is straightforward enough. Letâ€™s evaluate a less verbose collection of radial basis functions in the model.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df$pred_rad2 &lt;- as.formula(y ~ 0 + x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x6 + x10 + x12) %&gt;% 
  lm(data=df) %&gt;% 
  predict(df)</code></pre>

<p>The plot looks very similar.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data=df, aes(x, y), alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_line(data=df, aes(x, pred_floor), color='red', size = 1) +
  geom_line(data=df, aes(x, pred_rad2), color='steelblue', size = 1.5)</code></pre>

<p>Notice that the smoothed model still outperforms the dummy model and that I am using less dimensions of data while still maintaining a significant model.</p>

<div id="how-it-works" class="section level3">
<h3>How it works</h3>
<p>This may feel like voodoo to some. To give more of a visual feel for how this â€˜trickâ€™ works, Iâ€™ve plotted the resulting radial basis functions below.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mod_data &lt;- as.formula(y ~ 0 + x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x6 + x10 + x12) %&gt;% 
  lm(data=df) %&gt;% 
  tidy

rbf_effect &lt;- function(n){
  factor &lt;- mod_data %&gt;% filter(term == n) %&gt;% select(estimate) %&gt;% as.numeric
  df[[n]] * factor
}

vars &lt;- c('x1','x2','x3','x4','x6','x10','x12')
pltr &lt;- df 

for(v in vars){
  pltr[[v]] &lt;- rbf_effect(v)
}

pltr &lt;- pltr %&gt;% 
  select(x, x1, x2, x3, x4, x6, x10, x12) %&gt;% 
  melt(id.vars = c('x')) 

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data=df, aes(x, y), alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_line(data=pltr, aes(x, value, colour = variable), size =1.5) + 
  ggtitle('different RBFs with applied weights plotted with simulated data')</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>

<div id="conclusion" class="section level2">
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Weâ€™ve used a simple linear model here to keep the code from getting verbose but you can apply this feature generating technique in combination with many other approaches. This method especially seems to be a preferable method to model seasonality. Dummy variables tend to cause ugly jumps in the data and the only way to combat this is to up the dimensionality, which has onwanted side effects.</p>
